annotations.text:
SZA’s chorus invokes the feeling of “reaching for the stars” to achieve your dreams and/or chase success. The chorus also contains thematic connections to Black Panther comic book lore.

Stars are often symbolic of past spirits or supernatural beings watching over us. The Black Panther can commune with all previous Black Panther spirits to draw on their knowledge and expertise. Only the current Black Panther can do this, bringing him closer to his ancestors and their wisdom.



As part of his initiation into the role of the Black Panther, T'Challa is required to meet Bast the Panther Goddess. During T'Challa’s quest, Bast appears to T'Challa in his dreams. The powerful goddess Bast stood and asked T'Challa what his true desires were. He responded by stating that he wanted to serve his people, but he will be whatever Bast wants him to be. Bast then dubbed T'Challa her personal Black Panther and crowned him king of Wakanda’s Dead City. She referred to him as “King of the Dead” and stated that he will have the strength and knowledge of every Wakandan king laid to rest in the Necropolis.



Black Panther is the final movie before Avengers: Infinity War, a movie in which all of Marvel’s superheroes come together from every corner of the universe to fight their greatest adversary. The Marvel Cinematic Universe is finally shrinking, and bringing all the loose ends together.

Tell me what you gon' do to me (Do to me)

annotations.text:
Here, “the truth” might refer to the Word of God, as seen in John 14:6:

Jesus answered, ‘I am the way and the truth and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me.’

Kendrick Lamar grew up in the notorious streets of Compton, where gang confrontation was almost inevitable. For instance, Kendrick speaks on his trepidation concerning dying young in the second verse of “FEAR.”:

I’ll prolly die anonymous
I’ll prolly die with promises

Having survived the harsh conditions of his childhood, Kendrick proclaims that he does not fear conflict because he already believes in God’s Truth.

In the Black Panther comics, T'Challa is the sworn king and defender of Wakanda. Vibranium is the nation’s top resource and is virtually indestructible. But even these victories and seeming invulnerability can’t buy peace or truth. Kendrick uses this as a way to say that the truth comes from inside and knowledge of self rather than from anything external.

lines.text: Confrontation ain't nothin' new to me (New to me)
You can bring a bullet, bring a sword, bring a morgue
But you can't bring the truth to me (Truth to me)
Fuck you and all your expectations (Expectations)

annotations.text:
Like many MCs, Kendrick is known for bravado, breaking the mold, and making light of the acclaim he receives (e.g. DNA). Fresh off the success of DAMN., he is not interested in basking in accolades or accepting praise from former critics.

Similarly, Killmonger wastes no time politicking with former enemies. He is an unconventional Wakandan leader who is laser-focused on achieving his goals.

More broadly, this could be Kendrick preempting the praise that the film would receive by saying that an Afrocentric blockbuster never needed the approval of a Eurocentric society (and never needed to meet its expectations either).

lines.text: I don't even want your congratulations (Congratulations)
I recognize your false confidence and calculated promises

annotations.text: Kendrick is doing a couple of things here. First, calling back “real recognize real” and deploying the “real v fake” dichotomy often used by MCs. Also in keeping with the theme of the verse, he knows that people want something from him even though they may pretend not to. Second, as far as comics go, T'Challa/Black Panther is a master tactician and strategist in the Marvel Universe. An effective king is able to anticipate moves and to know the motivations and calculations of his enemies.

lines.text: All in your conversation (Conversation)
I hate people that feel entitled (Entitled)

annotations.text:
Kendrick feels that, due to his fame, people think they are entitled to his friendship.

Kendrick feels that the only person who is important is one who is “the moral to the story,” meaning he/she has the solution to the problem that has been plaguing the world for centuries: racism.

From the lens of the MCU, Black Panther is still a relatively new hero. Introduced in Captain America: Civil War, he has not yet had a major part in saving the world. But he owes nothing to the Avengers–he is the king of Wakanda and need not prove anything to the predominantly white “entitled” heroes.

lines.text: Look at me crazy 'cause I didn't invite you (Invite you)
Oh, you important? You the moral to the story? You endorsin'?
Mothafucka, I don't even like you (Like you)
Corrupt a man's heart with a gift (With a gift)

annotations.text:
This might be a reference to the biblical story of Adam and Eve, which explains man’s original sin.  Eve gave Adam the gift of an apple from the tree of knowledge, which corrupted them both and resulted in their expulsion from the garden of Eden—though it was the fault of the serpent who originally tricked Eve into eating the apple.

This could also be a reference to Ecclesiastes 7:7:

Surely oppression maketh a wise man mad; and a gift destroyeth the heart.

lines.text: That's how you find out who you dealin' with (Dealin' with)
A small percentage who I'm buildin' with (Buildin' with)

annotations.text:
In this verse Kendrick raps from a dubious, distrustful and hardhearted man’s perspective:

Fuck you and all your expectations
I don’t even want your congratulations.

This is why he states he is building his vision with “a small percentage” of people, because he has decided from past experiences that the majority of people aren’t trustworthy. Kendrick also raps about this same feeling of skepticism on “PRIDE.”

This “keep your circle small” mentality is a recurring theme in hip-hop. Tupac, one of Kendrick’s most noted influences, is often credited with the saying: “the realest people don’t have a lot of friends.”

This also relates to the Black Panther film since the main protagonist T'Challa had a small circle of people his trusted: his sister Shuri, his love interest Nakia, and his friend Okoye.

lines.text: I want the credit if I'm losin' or I'm winnin'

annotations.text:
This seems to follow a theme from “Real,” “You Ain’t Gotta Lie (Momma Said),” and even “HUMBLE.” In those tracks, Kendrick talks about being honest and genuine, rather than fake and misleading. “On my momma” means “I promise"—Kendrick wants to feel his success and failures.

In terms of rap battles, one of the best ways to preemptively silence an opponent is to admit to one’s own downfalls. This sentiment also applies to Kendrick’s life; he owns up to all his mistakes and victories–just as his momma raised him–and in doing so, he’ll always remain “the realest shit.”

In addition to this being a reference to taking an oath, this is added significance as a reference to Ramonda, T'Challa’s trusted confidant, adviser, and stepmother from Black Panther lore.

Skin covered in ego

annotations.text:
SZA likens her ego, or sense of self, to the indestructible metal Vibranium (Wakanda’s greatest natural asset) which renders Black Panther nearly impervious to physical attack.

https://qph.ec.quoracdn.net/main-qimg-56e094b3499db716aac61b7d99828ab3-c

SZA might also be referring to the color of her skin here. Personifying her blackness as her ego and part of her identity. Just like Black Panther wears a impervious black suit to fight and protect his people, she is also wearing her black skin to show her confidence or ego unapologetically.

Additionally, this phrase could the character Erik Stevens (aka Killmonger), whose skin is marked: one scar for every kill he’s made in the past. He oozes with confidence throughout the film, even at his low points.

lines.text: Get to talkin' like ya involved

annotations.text:
In the first lines of verse 2 SZA says her ego or self-confidence is like Wakanda’s Vibranium.

So, in this context she is saying that if anyone ever tried to hurt her or demean her or demotivate her it’ll just reflect to that person who sent this just like the Vibranium absorbs attacks and reflect it on the enemies on its wielder’s will.

Additionally, this line about the rebound goes with the next line which refers to being out of control, just like a rebound in basketball is a ball that can go in any direction when it rebounds off the hoop

lines.text: Like a rebound, no control

annotations.text:
SZA uses computer-related wordplay here. Computers have an on/off switch but also a Ctrl key (pronounced control). Perhaps like the machine itself, SZA’s actions are at the whim of the user, or in this case a person who might literally be using her (“know you mean wrong”). Alternatively she might not be functioning properly at all around this person, like a computer with no off-switch or Ctrl key.

SZA’s debut album was also titled Ctrl. The cover art depicted her with old, used computers.
